    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at buying my first place soon but i'm kinda confused about the different loan types. can u explain the difference between a fixed-rate mortgage and an adjustable-rate mortgage (arm)? specifically i wanna know how much my monthly payments might change over the first 5 years if i go with an arm vs a fixed one.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a fixed-rate mortgage, your monthly principal and interest payment stays the exact same for the entire loan term, offering predictable budgeting. Conversely, an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) has an introductory rate that can fluctuate with market indices, meaning your monthly payment could increase significantly within the first five years if rates rise. If you choose an ARM with an initial period of three or five years, you might see your payment increase by 20–50% annually during that time as it resets to the new market rate, whereas a fixed rate would grow by only about 6–8% annually due to long-term lending curves. Ultimately, an ARM carries higher uncertainty and risk during those early years compared to the stability of a fixed-rate loan.",
      "source": "target",
