      "content": "Yes, you are right; most ARMs today are indexed to South Texas Office Funding Rate (SOFR) instead of the older LIBOR index. While the index itself is largely unpredictable for individual borrowers, the adjustable rate floors it via the formula, typically allowing fluctuations of 2% to 3% per year above the initial rate based on market movements. Because the index is based on the broader economic climate, it is generally too volatile to plan around precisely, which is why many experts suggest avoiding ARMs if your financial situation isn't stable for the long term.",
